{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_brookland_ver01/data/sn84026749/00205696398/1930111301/0720.xml":{"full_text":"Financial Market News, Stocks, Bonds, Commodities and Comment\nNUT SHOWS\nITS STRENGTH\nBf RALLY\nTerrific Bearish Pressure\nLeaves Market Unaffected;\nTrend Upward Is Belief\nThe market has answered\nBy THE SPECTATOR\nthe question of whether It\nhad a rally left after the\nbattering It has been taking\nfor the last two weeks.\nStocks came back strongly\nyesterday after many had\nhit new lows for the year.\nRumors that a certain\n\u201csituation\u201d has been cleaned\nup, advance In copper prices\nand strength in the grain\nmarkets all helped. It looks\nas though the rally may go\na bit further, but I wouldn\u2019t\njump in and buy. I can\u2019t\nsee enough in it to warrant\nthe risk. There is still\nplenty of time to|>uy stocks.\nThe Coppers\nThe copper stocks were re\njuvenated by the announcement\nthat the price of the red metal\nhas been advanced to 10 cents a\npound. This is evidence that\ncopper producers have gotten to\ngether on curtailment of world\nproduction, and is welcome in\nview of the small decline in do\nmestic output in October and the\nincrease of stocks on hand.\nKennecott gave relatively the\nbest performance while all others\ngained substantially. But don\u2019t\nget excited about the coppers\nyet. They certainly are cheap\nif you are ready to be patient for\na couple of years or so; but. re\nmember that no producer is go\ning to get rich on 10 or even 11\ncent copper, and there are still\nmore than 600,000 tons above\nground.\nRadio is apparently lacking any\nkind of aggressive market spon\nsorship. It sank to a new low\nfor the year at 12% and was a\n\u201csick pup\u201d even when the rest\nof the market turned strong.\nThere has been a lot of dis\ngusted selling in Radio due to its\npoor earnings report for the nine\nmonths, showing a big deficit\nafter dividend requirements.\nAmerican Telephone\nFew believed that Telephone\nwould break 180, at which level\nit yields 5 per cent exclusive of\nits frequent rights, yet it did\nyesterday, dropping to 178 The\nmanner in which it rallied,\njumping 9 points from its low,\nsupports talk of bear pressure.\nStill a lot of the selling in this\npremier stock has been forced by\nliquidation of impaired accounts\nplus some frightened selling. The\nbears still say they are going to\nput it much lower, insisting that\nit Is out of line on earnings. Net\nfor the year is estimated at sll\na share. Yet I can\u2019t get bearish\non Telephone on a 5 per cent\nbasis. This is one dividend that\nseems absolutely safe. But no one\nshould buy Telephone or any\nstock these days for that matter,\nunless the transaction is prac\ntically cash.\nThe bears are certainly gun\nning after somebody in Fox.\nThere is said to be a big block\nof stock over-hanging the mar\nket, and the \u201cbad boys,\u201d \u2019tis re\nported, are after this. Fox\u2019s rally\nyesterday looked as though few\nshorts were- caught napping.\nThere is apparently a real\n\u201cscrap\u2019\u2019 in the stock, however,\nand it would be wise to avoid it\nfor the time being.\nErie\nThere has been quite a battle\nin Erie for several weeks. Bears\nhave put out some heavy short\nlines, stressing poor earnings,\nwhile bankers are said to have\nbeen supporting the stock. The\nbears scored yesterday by knock\ning it off about 4 points to a\nnew low. Erie\u2019s showing for the\nyear hasn\u2019t been encouraging,\nnet for the nine months being\nonly a few cents a share. There\nhas been some switching from\nErie to other stocks, especially to\nChesapeake and Ohio. The lat\nter for some time has been sell\ning less than 10 points higher,\npays a $2.50 dividend and is\nearning better than $4.. Erie\npays nothing.\n[equitable]\nCO-OPERATIVE BUILDING\nASSOCIATION\nOrranlied 1879\nMTH YKAB COMPLETED\ntweta 85,733,083.91\n3urpln\u00ab and Profit*.. 81.755.911.57\nJoin the Equitable and Save\nSystematically\nSubscriptions for the\n99TM ISSUE OF STOCK\nSharea 84.50 Per Month\nEQUITABLE BUILDING\n015 F Street N. W.\nJOHN JOT EDSON. Preaident\nWALTKB 8. PRATT. Jr.. Sec\u2019y\nA\nWEEKLY BUSINESS INDICATORS 7|\nREPRODUCED BY ARRANGEMENT WITH THE SURVEY OF CURRENT BUSINESS\nU. S. DEPARTMENT OF COMMERCE\nDATA PLOTTED, WHERE AVAILABLE FOR WEIK EHOIIM MOVEMBER,B 1930\na\nWEEKLY AVERAGE. 1923-1925. INCLUSIVE 100\n1930\nBITUMINOUS COAL PRODUCTION\nI XX 591\nxWsqpH\nLUMBER PRODUCTION**\nj -iJ'm\nioo n v\n80 Kz' (WxZ\ngflLd 1 1 111 11 1 Li 11 iulLu yll il liMLOTTI 1 1 ILxJ\nSTEEL INGOT PRODUCTION\n140 n \u2014ft \u2014n\u2014\"-'i\u2014\ni\u00bb -4.4\n100 A\n80\n60\n4ol.li.luiJm.llLi.ilii i 1 11 1 II I .Il I Lili II II 1 1.1 lid\nDETROIT FACTORY EMPLOYMENT*\n\u202250 r\u2014| \u2014r\u2014I \u2014IZT1\n.1 oo I 1 I t r\u2014 3*\nQ I I I I 11 I I I I I 11 ll I 11 11 1 I I I I ll UL.I I I I I I I I ULXL-\nPETROLEUM PRODUCTION iOAILY AVERAGE'\n>isor-- 1 \u2014r-y- T~|\nlaogttXggj \u2014n**\nf IqLm.l ,nL.\u25a0 Il.\u25a0. i....L\u25a0.i.mJ\u25a0 J; 1 JBfrtlMxlxM.\nFREIGHT CAR LOADINGS\n120, -t r\u2014 t~\n80*7-\n00 L J 1.111 1-1 11111 I I I I till I\u00bb$II\u00bb I I u Al lI.A-i.14 li Ill<l Li XL\nWHEAT REtfeIPTS\n400 i\u2014r \u2014r '-1 \u2014\u2014XT\u201c| T\n300 -1 4\n200M -1 4--in(Y\n0 nil,, 77 I'M 111 11 u. II I 1 1 1 M.\nCOTTON RECEIPTS\n400 r\u2014 t \u2014f \u2014i\nr rN~\n2001\u2014I\u2014 \u2014\u2018\u2014l\nI \u00b1~~jTT\n'Mf'oCtJ NOV OEG\ni\n\u2605BtLATION TO WEEKLY AVERAGES 1927 1929 Pte WttK SHOWR. *RELATIVt TO |92>\u00ab100\nGeneral Motors Proves\nHigh Wage Soundness\nShould wages be cut?\nNo, is the decisive answer of\nAlfred Pritchard Sloan, Jr., pres\nident. General Motors Corp. And\nMr. Sloan backs up his answer\nwith proof.\nThere has been lots of talk on\nboth sides of this question, but\nthis is the first time one of the\nbiggest industrial con\ncerns comes forward with proof\nthat cuts in wages are absolutely\nunnecessary.\nNo Cuts By Motors\nHere\u2019s what Mr. Sloan has to\nsay on the matter:\n\u201cGeneral Motors has not re\nduced either salaries or wages,\nand it is my hope that no re\nadjustment of that character\nwill be necessary.\n\u201cTo my mind it is important\nfor industry to appreciate the\nfact that the prosperity of the\nUnited Staes is founded on a\nhigh wage scale. To reduce\nthe wage scale would, in my\njudgment, not only delay the\nreturn of more normal times,\nbut would put a limit, and an\nunnecessary limit, on the fu\nture prosperity of the country.\n\u201cThe broader the margin\nthat exists between the daily\nwage and the necessities of the\nlife the more the individual\nhas available to purchase addi\ntional .products and enjoy and\nw. B. HIBBS CO.\nThe ONLY New York Stock Exchange House\nHaving Its Main Office in Washington\ni. MEMBERS\u2014\nNew York Stock Exchange\nBoston Stock Exchange\nPhiladelphia Stock Exchange\nWashington Stock Exchange\nNew York Cotton Exchange\nChicago Board of Trade\nAmerican Bankers Association\nDistrict Bankers Association\nHIBBS BUILDING\nNational 0540 WASHINGTON, D. C.\nTHE WASHINGTONTIMES\nBUllblNG CONTRACTS DAILY AVERAGE\n220 AANJ Rial MAR. IAPRJ BMY MM|\n\"f-=P^F\ni3\u00b0H \u2014TnHwdlrl \u2014myid \u2014\u2014frj\n4ql J.ll I. .1. .\u25a0I.II I I ly, I 111 I liu.ll mJ M I LM.\nCATTLE RECEIPTS\n180/\u2014\u2014 1- t 1\n100\na i\n50 i\n2gl LJ.II 111 I I IlluiL M.I II nJ 111 1 ILI ll \u201c111 n II 1 111 Ml\nHOG RECEIPTS\nl rfc-| \u2014\u2014\u2014I\nKfik I L*.\nH ryrt\n70 \u2014_\nIql. I I .1 \u25a0\u25a01.... 11 ..I. I.llllulll I lu.illlj\nFISHER\u2019S. WHOLESALE FRICE iNOtX*\n'\u201di 11'11 i ll riTn\n80 1\u2014\u2022 BBE\n80 LlI II 1 lllll\u25a0ll\u25a0 \u2018I \u201cI >mli 1111111 l IM I I I I I U1-\nWHEAT PRICE NO. 2 HARD.WINTER\nisor~ t T r--1 p-\u2019\n100 gs ss \u2022r* s*' 5\n1, ~1,,, I, 1.1 x 11L11.111 1 11111111\n\nCOTTON PRICE MIDDUNG. NEW YORK\n*t~ r~T~ I\u2014r~1 \u2014r~\neo 1\n4ql 1 1 11 111.111 im 1 1 u 1 umJiWl* 1 111 1 111\nTRON-AND STEEL UO&fWE \"PRICE\n8 0*! I\n\n70 H r i -H-\n60 J-mI Lm11.1111.1.1l .1.1.1 m. Lu.\nCOPPER PRICE? ELECTROLYTIC\n,i 0 LA :I I T\n|PBI CoHaai BMfe\n100\n80 ian fib'mar. Am ma* dudittf ote\nprofit by his leisure hours.\nThis development of purchas\ning power creates wealth,\nwhich, in turn, reacts and re\nacts throughout our whole in\ndustrial situation.\u201d\nThe proof of the wisdom of\nthis practice is found in General\nMotors\u2019 balance sheet, covering\noperations in the first nine\nmonths of this year\u2014the most\ntrying period of the depression.\nAt the end of September the\ncorporation had more than $145,\n000,000 in cash, nearly $42,000,-\n000 in United States Government\nsecurities and more than $14,000,-\n000 in other marketable securi\nties. This is a gain of $72,000,-\n000, in round numbers, in cash\nand securities since the end of\n1929,\nIn addition General Motors\nlopped more than $74,000,000 from\nits inventory account\u2014 that is,\nits supplies of new cars and raw\nmaterials were reduced that,much.\nGrounds for Optimism\nWhile the company\u2019s current\nassets were increased, its liabili\nties or debts were reduced some\n$33,000,000. The company now\nhas a surplus of more than $979,-\n000,000.\nThe company has been able to\ndo this without reducing wages\nand salaries and in the face of\ndeclining earnings.\nHead of Ford Ltd.\nTells Business Gain\nSir Percival Perry, European\ndirector of the Ford Motors Co.,\nLtd.; Maurice Dollful, French di\nrector, and Dr. Karl Wilhelm\nHauss, German director, arrived\nhere aboard the Lloyd line Bre\nmen. Commenting upon the cur\nrent business outlook of Ford in\nEurope, Sir Percival stated that\nin all countries, with the excep\ntion of Italy, where the Ford com\npanies were operating, business to\ndate was running ahead of last\nyear.\nContinuous Service\nCUSTOMERS of this house ore kept\nadvised of all important changes\neffecting their holdings. Earnings state*\nments are analyzed\u2014\u2018markets are con\nstantly checked and trends influencing\nbusiness and manufacturing lines care*\nBALTIMORE ,l y\nSTOCK EXCHANGES\nnw\u2019yorTcX your ,oek ond bond hold n 9* with u\nexchange so you may receive this service.\nMackubin, Goodrich Co.\nESTABLISHED IBW\nBAN KE RS\nMembers New York and Baltimore Stock Exchanges\nAssociate Member Npw York Curb Exchange\n1508 H STREET REDWOOD SOUTH STS.\nWASHINGTON, D. C BALTIMORE, MO.\n\nTh* National Dail*\nBANK DEBITS OUTSIDE NEW YORK CITY I\nwr,\n1201 XLkj I 1 J\nFIF 1 ViFuu n'Vi 1 1\nIQQ ill \u25a0ll iJin. 17.. 1... I\u00bby1 i/i... 1t.., I, .J\n\nLOANS AND DISCOUNTS FR. MEMBER .BANKS 1\nISOf 1 pr \u2014\u2014\u2014nr~iftc I 1\nf\n\n13011111 H 111 mJ u ill h.i 11 111 C\nr\nFEDERAL RESERVE RATIO\n20 rn \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014r~i \u2014\u2014\u2014m \u2014r-i\ni 1 00 V*\" 1 777 T 77T \u2014777 T\u2014~ t\nn,.\u00bb i...\nBA 18-.1 11 1 111 I 1 1 f Ikiulmil lii li mlml H .1.,, (ll\n\nCALL MONEY RATES\nSOOr\u2014 I\u2014rx-i1 \u2014rx-i 11 r~\u2019 T 8\nqI 111 I I MM.I I ImjL 111 Lxd UIIIII lUM 1111 I 1111L1 ll t\nJ\nSTOCK PRICES\nMO S Jy--\n100' 11M\u00bbLH1...Ja.L..1.uJ 1 1 1M.| 11 ..1.iil\ni\nBROKERS\u2019 LOANS\nJQqI 1,,, 1,,,, |i i!... .1... 1... 1,.. .1...1,. ..I. ..I j\nI\nTIME .MONEY rates j\n300 I\u2014r1 \u2014r- r- I \u2014T I\u20143 4\n1 4 8\n011( I I 111. 1.. J .Ml 11. 11m rill 111 c\nI f\nBONO PRICES j\nHO _\u00b1 nri\nI Os>>\u2014\n100-\"\"'\nBUSINESS FAILURES, NUMBER\n<BO n \u2014i \u2014\u2014\u2014r r ~i r~i\n,eo rlAl 1\n~rr-y y I\ni\n78 Mt rifc MAh MA* MN ML MM.IBW.Uct NWr Ittfc\nParis Banking Firm\nIs in Bankruptcy\nPARIS, Nov. 13.\u2014Benard Freres\nand Cie, a private bank of con\nsiderable importance before the\nwar, has been admitted to judicial\nliquidation. Difficulties arose\nafter the death of Marcel Benard.\nDespite The efforts of the sur\nviving brother, Georges, who is\nnow with Interstate Equities, it\nwas found advisable to apply to\nthe courts. Amount involved is\nabout 100,000,000 francs. Small\ncreditors have already been paid.\nTHURSDAY\u2014NOVEMBER 13\u20141930\nBILLION DOLLAR\nMERGEHOF\nSINCLAIR OFF\nNegotiations Defniitely Called\nOff Between Oil Firm and\nPipe Line Company\nCHICAGO, Nov. 13.\u2014Negotia\ntions for a billion-dollar merger\nbetween Sinclair Consolidated Oil\nCorporation and Prairie Oil and\nGas Company have been defi\nnitely discontinued because of\ninability to agree on terms satis\nfactory to both parties, Harry F.\nSinclair, chairman of the board\nof the former company, an\nnounced today.\nNegotiations for the merger\nhave been underway for more\nthan a year. The plan was for a\ncombination of Sinclair, Prairie\nOil and Gas Company and Prairie\nPipe Line Company. Negotiations\nalso were being carried on for\ninclusion of Tide Water Associ\nated Oil Company.\nThe first inkling that there was\nany hitch to the plan came\nfrom a statement made earlier\nthis week by W. S. Fitzpatrick,\nchairman of Prairie Oil and Gas.\nHe said:\n\u201cI feel we are farther from\nagreement now than I thought\nwe were some time ago.\u201d\nPipe Line Company Sold\nSinclair in July sold its half\ninterest in the Sinclair Pipe Line\nCompany and Sinclair Crude Oil\nPurchasing Company, to the\nStandard Oil Company of Indi\nana. Standard of Indiana owned\nthe other half interest. Standard\npaid Sinclair $72,500,000 in cash.\nThis was believed at the time\nto have paved the way for the\nPrairie-Slnclalr merger, as the two\nPrairie companies would bring to\nthe merger a crude oil purchasing\nand a pipe line companies.\nIt is not known whether the\nnegotiations will be resumed at\nsome later date, or Sinclair will\nseek to unite with some other\ncompany. In this connection ne\ngotiations now being carried on\nbetween Tide Water Associated\nand Richfield Oil Company of\nCalifornia, is another merger\nprospect.\nPantex Wins Suit\nIn Presser Patent\nPHILADELPHIA, Nov. 13\n(UP.). \u2014Victory was scored by the\nPantex Pressing Machine Com\npany. Pawtucket, R. 1., in litiga\ntion with the United States Hoff\nman Machinery Company, of Wil\nmington, Del., over two patents for\na suction drier for garment press\ning machines, when the United\nStates Circuit Court of Appeals\nruled the patents were invalid and\nthe Pantex Company not an in\nfringer.\nF. 0.8. Products\nSoar 9 Per Cent\nTabulation of the census ol\nmanufacturers for 1929 shows\nthat American manufacturers\nturned out goods valued at $68,-\n453,468,518. F. 0.8. factory\nprices. This is an increase of fl\nper cent over 1927, the last\npreceding year.\nThe number of wage earners\nincreased 2.4 per cent from 8,349,-\n755 to 8,550,284 and wages, 3.\u00a3\nper cent from $10,848,802,532 to\n$11,271,016,618.\nDeal Off ~~j\n11\ni w\nI IS gpxjg I\nr\n\u2014Time* Staff Photo\nHARRY F. SINCLAIR 1\nONE OF the leaders in the 1\n1 American oil Industry who told\nof ending of negotiations for a\nmerger between Sinclair Con-\nsolidated and Prairie Pipe Line.\nr No further deal is planned, he 1\nintimated.\niRADIOTUBESUIT.\nIS CLOSED\nI\nPHILADELPHIA, Nov. 13.\u2014 1\nThe United States District Court\nof Appeals here, by a vote of 2\n\u2022j to 1 of its judges, sustained a i\nsuit by the General Electric Com-\npany against the De Forest Radio\nCompany for infringement of the\nIrving Langmuir patent on radio\n1 vacuum tubes, which is uni\nversally used.\nBy the decision the court of\n1 appeals reverses itself in a rul\ni ing handed down in October,\n11929, in which it held the patent\nJ invalid. The court, however,\nafterward granted General Elec-\ntrie a rehearing and now has\nchanged the decision in favor of\n5 the General Electric Company.\n1 The decision is considered im-\nportant in the radio industry,\nand if it stands the test of an\n1 appeal to the Supreme Court it\nr will give to General Electric ex\nelusive control of the manufac\ntute and production of vacuum\n1 tubes such as are used in receiv\ning sets today.\nStock Speculation\nCuts Stamp Income\nt Sharp curtailment of stock\nL speculation has cut the Treas\n-3 ury\u2019s stamp tax revenue from\ni stock transfers almost in half.\ncompared with last year, it was\nlearned.\nIn the quarter ended Septem\nber 30, taxes amounted to $6,606,-\nr 548, against $11,920,696. Tax.col-\nlections on bonds and new Issues\n1 of stock dropped from $6,163,-\ns 420 to $4,812,649.\nBetter Auto Demand\nSpurs Sheet Plants\nMakers of steel sheets in\nYoungstown district are feeling\nt effects from resumption of auto\n(f mobile plants. Buying has im\ns proved for flat rolled steels.\ns zs\ny\n9\nt IMF* 11\nOJRp\nYou have already made up\nyour mind to save a portion\nof your earnings. The trou\nble is you have not started\nyet. Why put it off any\nlonger! Bring what you have,\nif it is only SI.OO, and open\na savings account today at\none of our convenient offices.\nYou will find it easy after\nthis beginning and the longer\nyou save, the easier it be\ncomes.\nWe will add 3%\ncompound interact\ni I -V*'\"\nThe Washington Loan and Trust Co.\nF Street at Ninth 17th Street ,at G\nJOHN B. LARNER, President\nResources Twenty Million Dollars\n11 1 1 \u2014sil\nINSULL, 71, SEES\nLOW MONEY AS\nBRIGHT SPOT\nEmployes and Associates Aid\nin Celebration of Natal\nDay of Utility Magnate\nCHICAGO, Nov. 13. (INK)\nSamuel Insull on his seventy-first\nbirthday took time to discuss the\ntrend of\u201e business, the future of\nthe civic opera and himself.\nHis friends and associates tele\nphoned congratulations, some of\nthe employe groups sent bouquets,\nand Mrs. Anna Peterson, direc\ntor of home economics for the\ngas company, followed her cus\ntom of 20 years by baking a\nbirthday cake bearing 71 candles.\nThe industrial depression, he\nsaid, is of major proportions, but\nin certain respects is far less\nacute than any that preceded it.\nA favorable aspect, he said, is\nthe plentiful supply of money.\nMr. Insull, when asked of busi\nness prospects, cited the record\nof his own companies. In so far\nas the utilities field is concerned,\nhe regards the depression as only\ntemporary and believes it will\nhave small effect on the growth\nof the companies.\nThe Civic Opera, one of Mr.\nInsull\u2019s paramount interests, has\nsuffered heavily in the depres\nsion, he said. He explained:\n\u201cOpera is a luxury, and lux\nuries always suffer first. How\never, I have no anxiety over\nthe ultimate course of the\nopera. It will grow as Chicago\ngrows and I have estimated\nthat the Chicago area will have\n9,000,000 population by 1965.\n\u201cRules of life? None, espe\ncially. I don\u2019t take outdoor ex\nercise at this time of year.\nNeither are my hours particu\nlarly regular. My only rule Is\nthat I never take a drink.'*\nExports of Wheat\nBest 1929 Levels\nNEW YORK, Nov. 13.\u2014Wheat,\nincluding flour, exports from the\nUnited States and Canada for the\nweek ending November 6 were\n6,851,445 bushels against 8,820,006\nbushels last week and 6,225,120\nbushels in the like week a year\nago.\nFor the 19 weeks ending Novem\nber 6, wheat exports were 157,346,-\n061 bushels, against 112,029,354\nbushels in the corresponding\nperiod a year ago.\nCorn exports for the week were\n5,922 bushels, against 5,118 bushels\nlast week and 21,184 bushels in\nthe like week a year ago.\nBudd Wheel Deal\nHeld Up by Court\nNEW YORK, Nov. 13 (INK).\nA temporary injunction and re\nstraining order was entered\nagainst the Trend Trading Serv\nice, Inc., as a corporation and\nE. E. Schmedt, as an individual,\nby Supreme Court Justice L. L.\nFawcett, as a result of alleged im\nproper dealings in a pool to boost\nBudd Wheel, Inc., stock.\n31","height":"30306","width":"24101"}}
